<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing white wine with fish versus red meat?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">White wines generally complement fish through their acidity, which enhances the delicate flavors without overwhelming them, while their lighter tannin structure won't compete with subtle seafood proteins. However, rich white wines like oaked Chardonnay or white Rhône blends can successfully pair with lighter red meats like pork or veal, especially when the preparation includes cream sauces or herbs that bridge the flavor gap.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve white wine at the same temperature for all food pairings?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">No, serving temperature should vary based on both the wine style and food pairing. Light, crisp wines like Sauvignon Blanc pair best with delicate dishes when served at 45-50°F to preserve their bright acidity, while fuller-bodied wines like aged Chardonnay benefit from slightly warmer temperatures (50-55°F) when paired with richer foods to allow their complex flavors to fully express themselves.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is white wine food pairing good for beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">White wine pairing is excellent for beginners because white wines generally offer more forgiving flavor profiles and fewer tannins that can clash with food. The basic principle of matching wine weight to food weight is easier to understand with whites, and classic pairings like Pinot Grigio with light pasta or Riesling with spicy cuisine provide clear examples of successful combinations that build confidence.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when pairing white wine with food?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is assuming all white wines are light and delicate, leading to mismatched pairings where bold, oaky Chardonnays overpower subtle dishes or crisp Albariño gets lost alongside rich, creamy sauces. Understanding that white wines range from bone-dry and mineral-driven to sweet and full-bodied is crucial for successful pairing.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I pair white wine with spicy food as effectively as red wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">White wines often pair better with spicy food than red wines because their lower alcohol and higher acidity help cool the palate rather than amplify heat. Off-dry white wines like Riesling or Gewürztraminer are particularly effective with spicy Asian or Mexican cuisine, as their residual sugar balances heat while their bright acidity cleanses the palate between bites.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I choose white wine for cheese pairings versus vegetable dishes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Cheese pairings typically require white wines with more structure and complexity—aged Chardonnay with creamy cheeses or Sancerre with goat cheese—while vegetable dishes often shine with crisp, herbaceous wines like Sauvignon Blanc that complement green flavors. The key difference is matching the intensity and richness of the pairing elements rather than defaulting to light wines for both scenarios.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are good white wine alternatives for people who typically drink red wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Red wine drinkers often enjoy full-bodied, oak-aged Chardonnays or white Rhône blends (Viognier, Roussanne, Marsanne) that offer similar richness and complexity to their preferred reds. Orange wines—white wines made with extended skin contact—provide tannin structure and depth that bridge the gap between white and red wine preferences while opening up unique food pairing possibilities.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I keep an opened white wine for food pairing purposes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most white wines maintain their pairing effectiveness for 3-5 days when properly stored in the refrigerator with a vacuum pump or inert gas system. However, very delicate wines like Muscadet or Vinho Verde lose their crisp character quickly and should be consumed within 1-2 days, while structured wines like aged Riesling or Chardonnay may actually improve slightly after a day of controlled oxidation.</p>
  </div>
